[Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican] I bind unto myself today The strong Name of the Trinity, By invocation of the same, The Three in One and One in Three.  2. [Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican, sacramental, baptism, baptismal-regeneration] I bind this day to me forever, By power of faith, Christ's Incarnation; His baptism in the Jordan river; His death on cross for my salvation; His bursting from the spiced tomb; His riding up the Heavenly way; His coming at the day of doom; I bind unto myself today.  3. [Tags: anglican, roman] I bind unto myself the power Of the great love of cherubim; The sweet "well done" in judgment hour; The service of the seraphim; Confessors' faith, apostles' word, The patriarchs' prayers, the prophets' scrolls; All good deeds done unto the Lord, And purity of virgin souls.  4. [Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican] I bind unto myself today The virtues of the starlit heaven, The glorious sun's life-giving ray, The whiteness of the moon at even, The flashing of the lightning free, The whirling wind's tempestuous shocks, The stable earth, the deep salt sea, Around the old eternal rocks.  5. [Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican] I bind unto myself today The power of God to hold and lead, His eye to watch, His might to stay, His ear to hearken to my need. The wisdom of my God to teach, His hand to guide, His shield to ward; The Word of God to give me speech, His heavenly host to be my guard.  6. [Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican] Against the demon snares of sin, The vice that gives temptation force, The natural lusts that war within, The hostile men that mar my course; Or few or many, far or nigh, In every place and in all hours, Against their fierce hostility I bind to me these holy powers.  7. [Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican] I bind unto myself the Name, The strong Name of the Trinity; By invocation of the same, The Three in One, and One in Three Of whom all nature hath creation; Eternal Father, Spirit, Word; Praise to the Lord of my salvation, Salvation is of Christ the Lord.  8. [Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican] Christ be with me, Christ within me, Christ behind me, Christ before me, Christ beside me, Christ to win me, Christ to comfort and restore me. Christ beneath me, Christ above me, Christ in quiet, Christ in danger, Christ in hearts of all that love me, Christ in mouth of friend and stranger.  9. [Tags: lutheran, ecumenical, anglican] I bind unto myself today The strong Name of the Trinity, By invocation of the same, The Three in One and One in Three. Of whom all nature hath creation; Eternal Father, Spirit, Word; Praise to the Lord of my salvation, Salvation is of Christ the Lord.

#Citations and References

Also known as: St. Patrick's Breastplate; The Deer's Cry (Fáed Fíada, Old Irish); Lorica of Saint Patrick. The Irish title "Fáed Fíada" ("Deer's Cry" or "cry of the stag") refers to a legendary account that St. Patrick and his companions were transformed into deer by God's protection as they travelled to Tara. The lorica (Latin: breastplate) form is a prayer of binding protection invoking the Trinity, Christ's saving acts, angels, saints, creation, and the divine presence. The stanza "Christ with me, Christ within me" (stanza 8) is frequently excerpted and used independently across all Christian traditions. Stanza 2 is the distinctly sacramental stanza, naming Christ's baptism in the Jordan alongside his Incarnation, Passion, and Resurrection as sources of spiritual power for the Christian life; this stanza accounts for the baptismal-regeneration tagging of the hymn. Stanza 3 is tagged anglican, roman (not lutheran) because its closing line — "And purity of virgin souls" — invokes the spiritual power of holy virgins as a source of protection, a form of appeal to the saints that is permitted in Anglican and Roman Catholic piety but is contrary to Lutheran doctrine, which holds Christ alone as mediator.

